      <heading>Sat Sep 21 (Haran)      :: RE: Treesing</heading>
      <slot>25</slot>
      <level>140</level>
      <author>0</author>
      <date>0</date>
      <text>I have to object to this policy.  I had a long conversation about it
with several people today and reasoned out my arguments against it.  I'm
not trying to be a rebel and I'm not going to break the policy as long
as it stands, but if you would, please give a little thought to this.

As I was discussing today, I reasoned there were two factors that brought
about the policy originally.  One was that the skill is very powerful,
capable of boosting stats on equipment permanently and setting the !break
flag.  The second was that the skill was abused.  So, instead of adressing
the problem directly, a policy was implemented putting a ban on OOC use of
the skill.

There were several alternatives to this that seemed wiser to me, though not
to everyone.  The first was that the skill itself should be restricted.  It
should be like Gate: you must earn it ICly through several RP sessions and
prove yourself worthy of getting it.  This would have prevented the abuse
directly, as only the most responsible and able players, ICly and OOCly,
would even have access to the skill.  This seemed the wisest move to me.

The second alternative that came to mind immediately was that the skill's
power be reduced.  The main reason that most people want the skill is for
the !break flag.  That keeps one from having to ever spend money to repair
and also enables one to use enhance without worry.  Though I didn't like
the solution, it would solve the problem.

The issues I have with policy as it stands is that it is so easy to break
and that I can't easily take hold of the one skill that I got after
becoming an Ogier.  This is selfish and greedy, but the mud is based off of
personal intrest.  The first policy I proposed would take care of the abuse
problem while still allowing those deemed worthy to reap the benefits of
the skill without the hassle of having to RP every time.

Sorry to dump this on you so soon after your instatement, Gaurav, but your
post reminded me of the grudge I've long held against this policy.  That
and the fact that I'm feeling just especially argumentative today.
-Haran-
</text>
    </message>
