    <message>
      <heading>Sat Sep 21 (Gaurav)     :: Re:Treesinging part 1</heading>
      <slot>27</slot>
      <level>203</level>
      <author>0</author>
      <date>0</date>
      <text>Hello ALL,
&amp;n
Let's see if I can reply to post 25 and 26 without ruffling any feathers here.  However before I make my points why we should have this policy allow me to point out one simple thing A Sung items is special to every Ogier.   With that in mind I find it hard to justify allowing anyone to play the part of a Sung Pimp (poor choice of words but the point is made).
&amp;n
Breaking down the points from posts 25 &amp; 26 I see that:
1. Why was this policy made?
2. Alternatives to the Policy
3. Problems with policy
4. Few items to actually sing IC 
&amp;n
Well please allow me to address them in order I have listed.  
&amp;R
1. Why was this policy made?
Haran is correct OOC'ly this is a powerful skill, which bumps ac, abs, hit, damage and prevents the item from every breaking.  Coupling this skill with the enhance skill switches a common every day item into a very good one.  Although that alone does not raise any flags in my eyes.  Why?  In my eyes this is the Ogiers version of channeling therefore it should be powerful.  When an Ogier sings to a tree the items gained are gifts from the tree.  They are created from the tree without damage to it.  That in itself is a wondrously boggling concept.  Think of it like this, the joy of creation without harming anything.  To me this is very special.
However the abuse of the skill is/was something very real here on fang.  I have seen Ogiers who are still active in our guild sing items for people without so much as a RP session, and in the center of Caemlyn nonetheless.  As one of my alts I paid 1k an item for a total of 10k (10 items) in the center of Caemlyn and had a very nice sung eq kit.  Was this fun for anyone but my alt who wanted to level?  I do not think so.  Although I will admit it did make the Ogier some money, and perhaps raise his skill slightly.
&amp;R
2. Alternatives to the policy
The idea of limiting who gets treesinging is something I was considering adding to the policy when I posted it, however I wanted to speak with the guild before I put that in.  My idea is pretty simple.  The guild rank of treesinger at the moment has 3 subranks, which I would like to change to 4.  The new subranks would be Innate, Apprentice, Journeyman, and Master.  Adjusting the treesinging skill to fit each person I figured that we could set the skill at:&amp;c
Innate: Treesinging 1%
Apprentice: Treesinging 25%
Journeyman: Treesinging 50%
Master: Treesinging 90%&amp;R
Thus through RP with a Journeyman or Master the Innate/Apprentice can gain IC understanding of the skill and move on to the next skill level.  The Journeymen RP would be his own leading her/him someday to become a master in the art of Treesinging.  The key here is Role-playing.  Since this guild is a RP guild, the knowledge of the skill should be RP'ed.  To help in this I will contact the current Treesingers and try to set up a syllabus for treesinging.
Personally though I do not see power reduction for this skill doing anything to change my mind about how it should be used.  As I stated earlier in this post, the Sung items should be special to Ogiers since the skill is not as common today as it was in the Age of Legends.&amp;n
</text>
    </message>
    <message>
      <heading>Sat Sep 21 (Gaurav)     :: Re:Treesinging part 2</heading>
      <slot>28</slot>
      <level>203</level>
      <author>0</author>
      <date>0</date>
      <text>cont. from post 27
&amp;R
3. Problems with Policy
Using real life as example you can break any law/policy/standard you wish.  When you break it most likely you will not get caught.  So why follow them?  Respect for what they stand for.  This policy does not hinder anyone from treesinging an IC item, however it does simply state that you RP doing it.  Adding too that common sense (like a tree can not make a metal breastplate) we arrive at where the policy stands today.
On the issue of reduction of personal fun, I cannot honestly share my thoughts on that, since each person defines her/his own fun.  However I can pose a couple of questions and we can see how I line up with your answers:  
&amp;rWhy is singing an item fun when you only get paid? &amp;YFor me it would not be.
&amp;rDoes lack of RP = Fun? Or does RP = Fun?  &amp;YI would pick the second.
&amp;rAre there creative ways to get around the singing policy and still follow it to the letter? &amp;YYes.
&amp;R
4. Few items to actually sing IC
That is correct.  There is a limitation with everything.  Channelers must grasp the one power to perform their weaves, well my furry-eared friends
we must embrace a tree to accomplish our magic.  With that said, a creative person could find ways a sung item could be more readily found.  A few ideas here a wooden charm worn on a necklace or on a bracelet, perhaps a wooden bowl, maybe wooden shield? Those are just a few ideas I thought up in 10 seconds, think about what could be accomplished with 30 minutes of RP.
&amp;n
&amp;n
My goal here was not to attack each point however it does seem like what I have done.  Please allow me to offer a very honest apology for that.  It was neither my goal in starting nor my goal in finishing this post to do so.
&amp;n
Thanks for you time, and let me know if this made any sense (wrote this last night at 4a.m.).
Gaurav's puppetmaster
</text>
